			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3035">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Cheryl Strayed&rsquo;s essay about her mother&rsquo;s death [&ldquo;<a href="/article/2192">The Love of My Life</a>,&rdquo; September 2002] reminded me of the death of my beloved grandmother in the midseventies.</p>

<p>The day of her funeral was breezy and sunny. The minister from the local funeral home, who clearly had never met my grandmother, delivered a canned eulogy. I wished that I could have spoken instead of him. As I stood by her grave and watched them lower in the coffin, I thought, <em>There goes my little grandmother</em>. And suddenly I wanted to throw myself on top of her coffin. I wanted to lie down in the dirt and pull my hair out and shriek. I wanted to make sounds I&rsquo;d never made in my life, sounds I couldn&rsquo;t even imagine.</p>

<p>Instead, in the reserved way of my family, I let the tears roll down my cheeks and sobbed only after I got into the car.</p>

<p>I don&rsquo;t know why people think grief is supposed to end. Our culture wants us to follow a set of rules or take some kind of pill for grief and relabel it &ldquo;depression.&rdquo; But despair is not depression. The pills are useless when these feelings arise from real causes, not just a chemical imbalance in the brain. No one has a pill for grief. Grief simply has to be taken on its own terms and lived through. No one ever said that life was supposed to be painless or that we will know exactly how to deal with every feeling that comes our way. We do what we do, and sometimes we do very self-destructive things without understanding why.</p>

<p>Most of us just put one foot in front of the other and, somehow, we survive. But advice to &ldquo;let it go&rdquo; and &ldquo;move on with your life&rdquo; should be banned from polite conversation. Let go of the most important and powerful relationship in your life? Of course, one does move on, one way or another, but that doesn&rsquo;t mean the grief is any less or the pain somehow magically cured. As Strayed says, life isn&rsquo;t like fiction. Losing something priceless doesn&rsquo;t make everything right again. One simply feels the grief less intensely as time passes. But the grief never really goes away.</p>

<p>In March I had to put down my thirteen-year-old dog because she had bone cancer. About two weeks later, I dreamed she was living in Ohio with my grandparents. She was three again, her best age. I hugged her and rubbed snow into her fur, telling her she was my &ldquo;snow doggie.&rdquo; When I woke up, I wanted to be with her more than anything. I wanted to be dead, because I know when I die I&rsquo;ll be with my dog and my grandmother again, and I&rsquo;ll be twelve years old, my best age. I can&rsquo;t imagine anything more comforting. I miss my dog every day. I don&rsquo;t want a new dog, a different dog; I want my Molly.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Saralyn F. Fosnight<br>Otis, Massachusetts</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3036">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I have been a psychotherapist for more than twenty-six years, and I can confirm that Cheryl Strayed&rsquo;s essay details the reality of grief, of our culture&rsquo;s denial, and of true healing. &ldquo;What does it mean to heal? To move on?&rdquo; she writes. &ldquo;It is usually said and not done, and the people who talk about it the most have almost never had to do it.&rdquo;</p>

<p>It is horribly sad when psychotherapy gurus promote a coping strategy that denies us our grief and promotes the cultural mystification of it.</p>

<p>I will share Strayed&rsquo;s essay with many of my clients in hopes that it will help them to face the real problem: that of refusal to see, to be aware, to experience life as it is.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Mark Kircher<br>Boise, Idaho</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

